name.treatmentStandardsRoutes: residential heating systems from wood pellets, boiler, max. heat output 14,9 kW

dataSetInformation.common:generalComment: A detailed model of a wood pellets boiler was used, which combines measured emissions taken from several studies plus calculated values for not measured emissions of e.g. sulphur in the condensate and sulphur dioxide emissions in the exhaust gas.

locationOfOperationSupplyOrProduction.descriptionOfRestrictions: Average data, no individual sub-locations explicitly considered.

technology.technologyDescriptionAndIncludedProcesse: The data set represents the currently used technical standard of newly installed residential heating systems. The heat is produced in a wood pellet boiler with a maximum heat output of 14,9 kW, used as residential heating system. The woodden pellets are stored in a storage room, automatically transfered to the hopper reservoir via a conveying screw or a induced-draft blower. Another conveying screw is transporting the pellets to the burner bowl. In the bottom of the burner bowl there are holes which can be opened to release the ash. The combustion is easily controlled and has low emissions due to the small firebed. A buffer storage (100 liter) for the hot water is included as it reduces the otherwise necessary pulsing and therefore the emissions. Region specific technology standards regarding efficiency and firing technology are considered. Furthermore the data set comprises the production of the device, its end-of-life as well as the pellet production. Wooden pellets are made of waste wood as saw dust, wooden strands, swarf and logging remains. These are compressed and pelletized into standardized dimensions by means of a ring or plate shaping die. The background system is addressing the use of electricity as follows: The electricity used is an average of the electricity used in EU-27 which is derived from the electricity data sets modelled according to the individual country-specific situations. The country-specific modelling is achieved on multiple levels. Firstly the individual power plants in service are modelled according to the current national grid. This includes net losses and imported electricity. Second, the national emission and efficiency standards of the power plants are modelled. Third, the country-specific fuel supply (share of resources used, by import and / or domestic supply) including the country-specific properties (e.g. element and energy contents) are accounted for. Fourth, the import, transport, mining and exploration processes for the energy carrier supply chain are modelled according to the specific situation of each power-producing country. The different mining and exploration techniques (emissions and efficiencies) in the different exploration countries are accounted for according to current engineering knowledge and information. Transports: All relevant and known transport processes used are included. Overseas transports including rail and truck transport to and from major ports for imported bulk resources are included. Furthermore all relevant and known pipeline and / or tanker transport of gases and oil imports are included. Energy carriers: Coal, crude oil, natural gas and uranium are modelled according to the specific import situation (see electricity).
technology.technologicalApplicability: Heat on a temperature level of ca. 70°C at the outlet of the heating system with the purpose of residential heating.

LCIMethodAndAllocation.deviationsFromLCIMethodApproaches: All allocations are used in the upstream processes. For the combined crude oil, natural gas and natural gas liquids production allocation by net calorific value is applied. For the combined heat and power production, allocation by exergetic content is applied. For the electricity generation and by-products, e.g. gypsum, allocation by market value is applied due to no common physical properties.
LCIMethodAndAllocation.modellingConstants: An annual use efficiency of 84% was taken into account for the heating system. The annual use efficiency is the ratio of produced heat to fuel input during one year, with an average max. of 90% related to the net calorific value. All data used in the calculation of the LCI results refer to net calorific value. For the transport of energy carriers average transport processes with specific parameter settings e.g. transport distances and route (ship, pipeline, rail, road) are used.

dataSourcesTreatmentAndRepresentativenes.dataCutOffAndCompletenessPrinciples: Cut-off rules for each unit process: Coverage of at least 95 % of mass and energy of the input and output flows, and 98 % of their environmental relevance (according to expert judgement).
dataSourcesTreatmentAndRepresentativenes.deviationsFromCutOffAndCompletenessPrinc: The coverage for the exploration data (crude oil, natural gas, natural gas liquids) is only 90% of mass and energy and 95% of the environmental relevance (expert judgement).
dataSourcesTreatmentAndRepresentativenes.dataSelectionAndCombinationPrinciples: The data sources for the complete product system are sufficiently consistent: The key emissions of the heating system (carbon monoxide, volatile organic compounds, nitrogen oxides, polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons, dioxin, dust, nitrogen oxides, hydrochloric acid, and dinitrogen oxide) are measured values taken from studies. Few other emissions from the heating system are calculated via energy carrier composition in combination with (literature-based) combustion models (eg. sulphur dioxide ). The data on the wood pellet supply chain is based on industry and literature data on the inventory of production. LCI modelling is fully consistent.
dataSourcesTreatmentAndRepresentativenes.dataTreatmentAndExtrapolationsPrinciples: Data measured at a group of representative heating systems have been used to represent the European average. The measurements are taken from studies conducted in Germany, Austria and Switzerland. The used technology is representative for EU-27.

dataSourcesTreatmentAndRepresentativenes.useAdviceForDataSet: The data set represents the life cycle of the heating system and the cradle to gate inventory of the energy supply. It can be used to characterise the whole supply chain for heat used for residential heating. The data set comprises the inventory up to the outlet of the heating system and a buffer storage for hot water. It excludes the system components necessary to distribute the heat in the house and eventually to combine it with other heating sources. Combination with individual unit processes using this commodity enables the generation of user-specific (product) LCAs.

review.common:reviewDetails: Inventory: The internal review was done by several iteration steps concerning raw data validation, raw data documentation, representativity, completeness and consistency of modelling with regard to ISO 14040 and 14044.; Documentation: The review of the documentation was performed by Ecobilan and is in compliance with ISO 14040 and 14044. The data set documentation is correct in view of the appropriateness of the information provided. It includes all relevant information in view of data quality and scope of application of the respective LCI result.

common:commissionerAndGoal.intendedApplications: This background LCI data set can be used for any types of LCA studies.

publicationAndOwnership.common:accessRestrictions: The data set can be used free of charge by anybody to perform LCA studies, to distribute it to third parties, to convert it to other formats, to develop own data sets etc. as long as the copyright and license conditions for the ELCD data sets and the ILCD format are met that can be accessed via http://lca.jrc.ec.europa.eu. Please note e.g. that reference must be given to the 'Owner of data set' and to the 'ELCD database' plus version number, when using the data set or parts thereof. Please note also, that any modifications/omissions of the data set results in invalidity of any existing 'Official approval of data set by producer/operator', that the impression must be avoided that this would still be a complete ELCD data set, and that the content of further fields has to be adjusted. For details see the aforementioned copyright and license conditions.
